    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA353-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu tōḻi āṟṟatu arumai añci tāṉ āṟṟāḷāyc colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what the confidante said, being herself unable to bear it, afraid of the difficulty of [his] path.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA353">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            āḷil peṇṭir tāḷiṟ ceyta</l>
<l>            nuṇaṅkunuṇ paṉuval pōlak kaṇaṅkoḷa</l>
<l>            vāṭumaḻai tavaḻuṅ kōṭuyar neṭuvarai</l>
<l>            muṭamutir palaviṉ kuṭamaruḷ perumpaḻaṅ</l>
<l>            kalluḻu kuṟavar kātaṉ maṭamakaḷ</l>
<l>            karuviraṉ mantikku varuvirun tayarum</l>
<l>            vāṉṟōy veṟpa cāṉṟō yallaiyeṅ</l>
<l>            kāmaṅ kaṉiva tāyiṉum yāmat</l>
<l>            tirumpuli tolaitta peruṅkai yāṉai</l>
<l>            veñciṉa murumi ṉuraṟu</l>
<l>            mañcuvaru ciṟuneṟi varuta lāṉē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>          O man from the sky-touching mountain,</l>
<l rend="indent">          where the beloved inexperienced daughter of the stone-ploughing</l>
<l rend="indent">           hill people</l>
<l rend="indent">          prepares<note place="foot">Here <term xml:lang="ta">viravu ayarum</term> certainly has to be understood as a transitive. That calls into question all the other passages where it seems to work intransitively. Is simply both possible? Or is the point always preparing a festival for some one (usually HIM who is coming back), even if that is elliptical?</note> a feast to come to the black-fingered female monkey:</l>
<l rend="indent2">          a pot-like big fruit of the bent old jack tree</l>
<l rend="indent2">          on the high long mountain with peaks covered in playing clouds</l>
<l rend="indent3">          in groups, as very fine cotton</l>
<l rend="indent3">          made by the effort of manless women,</l>
<l rend="indent4">          you are not worthy,</l>
<l>        because of coming by the fearful small path,</l>
<l rend="indent">          where the large-trunked elephant that had destroyed a tiger</l>
<l rend="indent2">          roars like thunder in hot anger,</l>
<l rend="indent3">          at midnight, even if our desire is at melting point.</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
